args: The orchestra has received a letter—\nand look at the sender!
She's offering to perform with us!
Did you ask her to do this, Vixel?
You were with her in the choir, right?
I was, yes—but this wasn't me.
Well, we've been doing brilliantly lately,\nso maybe she's anticipating even greater\nthings from us!
I don't know...although it IS true we've had\na successful run since Vixel joined us.
Regardless of the reason, this is a\nfantastic opportunity for us.
We would be fools to turn it down!
We're going to do it, right, Vixel?
I need to think about this.
Geez, he just turned around and left.\nDo you think something's wrong?
Heh. I can't believe you knew it was me\njust from the sound of my knock.
Oh, that? It's nothing. Now then,\nwhat do you need?
Based on your tone of voice, I assume the\norchestra members implored you to come\nhere and check on me.
Pretty much, yes. They also told me all\nabout Lucretia's offer—in rather breathless\ntones, I might add.
You'd be sure to draw a huge crowd if she\nsang with you, and the orchestra itself\nis practically bursting with excitement.
You know, I had a friend who once told\nme that you can often find better answers\nWITH someone than you can alone.
And look, I'll be the first to admit I'm an\namateur when it comes to music...
But I'd like to help you the way you\nhelped me.
...Or would you rather talk to\nsomeone else?
No, it's nothing like that. This is actually\na great deal of hullabaloo for what is,\nat heart, a rather trivial matter.
Honestly, if we were to discuss it, I fear\nyou might end up disillusioned with me.
You're my friend, Vixel.\nThat would never happen.
Very well, then. I am frightened.
I know well what a talent Lucretia is.
I was thought of as something of a prodigy\nin my choir days, but the moment she\nappeared, I was all but tossed aside.
It was almost like she was blessed by\nsome musical deity.

Well, this gave me the excuse I needed to
abandon singing when my voice changed.
It was regrettable, of course, but also
something of a relief.
And yet, if I am to conduct, I must once\nagain face the singer who unnerved me\nenough to force a change of career.
Lucretia has actually offered to perform\nwith me countless times before this.
She doubtless sees through my cowardice.\nAnd yet, I've not once taken her up on it.

I'm not confident I can deliver a
performance that lives up to the
singing voice of the person who
drove me to quit.
Well, maybe you should turn her down\nthis time, too.
This is an unmatched opportunity for\nthe orchestra.
But if their conductor is wracked with\nunease, I don't know how they'll be\nable to put on a good performance.
Either way, the decision is yours.\nJust make sure you have no regrets.
When my voice changed, it...hurt me.\nI didn't want to face that pain, and so\nI chose to run instead.
I dedicated myself to finding a path\nthrough life where I would never again\nhave to face such pain.
But I was wrong—you can't run from\nsomething like that. It just follows you\nabout like some kind of curse.
I regret that I ran. I regret my cowardice.
It's strange to hear this coming from\nsomeone as accomplished as you.

I've told you many times over that you
think too highly of me, have I not?
I'm not a man of any real import—
in fact, I'm not even a man.
I'm not sure I agree. But even so,\ncan you really keep going like this?
The way you talk about this makes it seem\nlike your mind is already made up.
If I were to run again now, it would be the\nsame as the first time I did.
I cannot remain that young boy forever.
Between you, her, and the orchestra,\nit's going to be a smashing success!
I will give my all in order to live up to\nthose expectations.
I gave in to my weakness back then,\nand surrendered what most mattered\nto me.
I don't want to lose anything else—\nleast of all my career as a conductor.
I won't run anymore. I'm going to fight\nthrough this and grow up in the truest\nsense of the term.
